    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Preventing Child Abuse</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brian O'Meara letter scores system for imposing insufficient punishment for employees of Mississippi Division of Youth Services who abused children in their care (Sept 1 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A society that does not punish a class of crimes condones those crimes. The worst punishment received by employees of the Mississippi Division of Youth Services who physically abused children, denied them medical care and locked them naked in dark cells for days was a six-week suspension (''Care of Juvenile Offenders in Mississippi Is Faulted,'' news article, Sept. 1).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A society that does not punish a class of crimes condones those crimes. The worst punishment received by employees of the Mississippi Division of Youth Services who physically abused children, denied them medical care and locked them naked in dark cells for days was a six-week suspension (''Care of Juvenile Offenders in Mississippi Is Faulted,'' news article, Sept. 1).</p>
        <p>There will be no justice for these children or for other forgotten and abused children throughout the nation until society starts meting out proportionately severe punishments for these abhorrent crimes.</p>
        <p>BRIAN O'MEARA  Davis, Calif., Sept. 2, 2003</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
